description: From Doug Yanega at UC Riverside: a mating ball of Diadasia bituberculata, a native cactus bee that nests in the ground. Males of this and many other bee species emerge about a week ahead of the females, and they wait - and wait - until a female starts to burrow up to the surface, detecting her by sound and pheromones. As soon as she breaks free of the dirt, a ball of males will form around her, all scrambling to be the one that gets to mate.
